			<p>Catering for fifty people sounds simple until you're standing in a kitchen at 11:45 AM realising the food is late, the dietary labels are missing, and the meeting starts in fifteen minutes. After fifteen years of catering Vancouver offices — from boardroom lunches to all-hands gatherings to multi-day conferences — we've learned that big group catering is less about quantity and more about discipline. Here's how to get it right.</p>

			<h2>Get the <em>Headcount</em> Three Days Out</h2>

			<p>The single biggest source of stress in office catering is unclear guest counts. We always recommend confirming a final number 48–72 hours before the event. Too late and the kitchen scrambles. Too early and you risk over-ordering or showing up with not enough food.</p>

			<p>Build a rhythm with your team: send the calendar invite a week out, send a reminder for RSVPs three days before, and lock the count two days before delivery. This small discipline solves 80% of office catering problems.</p>

			<h2>Always Plan for <em>10–15% More</em></h2>

			<p>Even with confirmed RSVPs, plan for slightly more food than your final headcount. Surprise visitors, second helpings, and post-meeting takeaway containers all eat into your buffer. For 50 confirmed guests, plan portions for 55–60. The extra cost is minimal and the alternative — running out of food — is far worse.</p>

			<h2>Dietary Restrictions <em>Aren't Optional</em></h2>

			<p>For any office of 50+ people, you'll have a mix of vegetarians, vegans, gluten-free, halal, and probably at least one nut allergy. Treating these as edge cases is how teams end up with hungry employees and quiet resentment.</p>

			<p>What works:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Always include a vegetarian main, ideally vegan</li>
				<li>Have at least one gluten-free option clearly labelled</li>
				<li>For halal needs, work with a caterer that sources halal-certified meats by default</li>
				<li>Label every dish with allergens (nuts, dairy, gluten, sesame)</li>
				<li>Ask about restrictions in your RSVP form, not in the room</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Hot Food Needs <em>Hot Delivery</em></h2>

			<p>Indian food is at its best when it's hot. Lukewarm dal makhani is sad dal makhani. For office catering, ask your caterer specifically how they transport hot food. The answer should involve insulated, temperature-controlled containers that maintain food-safe temperatures from kitchen to your office.</p>

			<p>If the food has to sit for an hour before service, ask about chafing dish setup. For meetings of 50+, a simple buffet line with two chafing dishes per hot course will keep things flowing without bottlenecks.</p>

			<h2>Buffet vs. <em>Boxed Meals</em></h2>

			<p>For meetings under 90 minutes, individually packed boxed meals often work better than buffets. People grab and go, the meeting starts on time, and there's no buffet line bottleneck. Boxed meals also handle social distancing concerns gracefully if your office has them.</p>

			<p>For longer events — half-day workshops, all-hands, conferences — a buffet creates better energy and lets people customise portions. The trade-off is a 15-minute serving window. Plan accordingly.</p>

			<h2>The Indian Menu That <em>Always Works</em></h2>

			<p>After hundreds of Vancouver office lunches, here's the menu structure that consistently delivers:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>One vegetarian curry that's a crowd-pleaser (paneer butter masala, palak paneer, dal makhani)</li>
				<li>One non-vegetarian curry (chicken tikka masala or butter chicken — yes, classics for a reason)</li>
				<li>One rice (basmati or pulao)</li>
				<li>One bread (naan or roti)</li>
				<li>A starter or chaat counter for variety</li>
				<li>One simple dessert (gulab jamun, ras malai, or kheer)</li>
				<li>Salad and pickles on the side</li>
			</ul>

			<p>This covers 95% of dietary preferences and works for almost any meeting type.</p>

			<h2>Recurring Programs <em>Save Time</em></h2>

			<p>If your team eats together regularly — weekly Friday lunches, monthly all-hands, recurring training days — set up a rotating menu with your caterer. We work with several Vancouver companies on weekly programs where the menu rotates through 6–8 chef's selections. This keeps things fresh without requiring you to make decisions every week.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

			<p>Office catering isn't glamorous, but it's deeply important. A well-fed team works better, longer, and happier. A poorly-catered meeting plants quiet frustration that lingers all afternoon. The difference between the two is rarely the food itself — it's the discipline behind getting it right.</p>

